<h1>Naming Standards Documentation</h1>

<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>The purpose of this document is to establish a standardized naming convention for resources deployed in Microsoft Azure by OPPD. This convention aims to promote consistency, clarity, and efficient management of Azure resources.</p>

<h2>Standard</h2>
<p>The Azure Naming Convention standard for OPPD Company is as follows:</p>

<h3>2.1 General Naming Guidelines</h3>
<p>There are several best practices from Microsoft that companies should follow to ensure consistency and avoid confusion. The key is to maintain consistency and ensure that the names provide clear information about the resource's purpose, environment, and role within the system. Here are some recommended naming conventions:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Consistency:</strong> All resource names should follow a consistent format and pattern.</li>
    <li><strong>Descriptive and Meaningful Names:</strong> Resource names should accurately reflect their purpose or function.</li>
    <li><strong>Use lowercase letters:</strong> All resource group/resource names should be in lowercase letters. This helps ensure consistency and makes it easier to read and type.</li>
    <li><strong>Case Sensitivity:</strong> Resource names are case-insensitive.</li>
    <li><strong>Use hyphens to separate words:</strong> When naming resources, use hyphens to separate words instead of spaces. For example, instead of "Virtual Network 1," use "vnet-001."</li>
    <li><strong>Be descriptive:</strong> Use descriptive names that provide context about the resource's purpose and function. For example, instead of "virtual network 1," use "vnet-gis-prod-svc-cus-001."</li>
</ul>

<p><code>[resource type]-[application]-[environment]-[resource group name]-[az location]-[instance]</code></p>

<p><strong>Include the environment:</strong> When creating resources for different environments such as development, test, QA, UAT and production, include an environment identifier in the name. For example, "rg-gis-dev-svc-cus-001" or "rg-gis-prod-svc-cus-001."</p>

<p><code>[resource group]-[application]-[environment]-[resource group name]-[az location]-[instance]</code></p>

<p><strong>Use consistent naming across subscriptions:</strong> If there are multiple Azure subscriptions in OPPD tenant, use consistent naming conventions across all subscriptions to ensure clarity and consistency. For example, “Oppd-Gis-Non-Production” or “Oppd-Gis-Production”.</p>

<h3>Resource Group (rg)</h3>
<p><strong>Environment abbreviation:</strong></p>
<ul>
    <li>P = Production</li>
    <li>T = UAT</li>
    <li>Q = Quality Assurance</li>
    <li>D = Development</li>
    <li>M = Demo</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Region abbreviation (optional):</strong></p>
