<h3>Virtual Machines (VMs)</h3>
<p>(Note: We are following OPPD on-prem standards for VMs and SQL instances naming conventions. We are not using hyphens to separate words)</p>

<p><strong>Description of the Naming Scheme</strong></p>
<p>The naming scheme is composed of a series of parts, with each part serving a particular purpose.</p>

<p><strong>Platform</strong></p>
<p>Format: One (1) alphabetic character</p>
<p>Purpose: Describes the operating system that the host utilizes.</p>
<p>Examples:</p>
<ul>
    <li>W = Windows</li>
    <li>X = Unix</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Form Factor</strong></p>
<p>Format: One (1) alphabetic character</p>
<p>Purpose: Describes the form factor.</p>
<p>Examples:</p>
<ul>
    <li>P = Physical</li>
    <li>V = Virtual</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Region</strong></p>
<p>Format: One (1) alphabetic character</p>
<p>Purpose: Describes the SDLC region that the host is considered a part of.</p>
<p>Examples:</p>
<ul>
    <li>P = Production</li>
    <li>T = UAT</li>
    <li>Q = Quality Assurance</li>
    <li>D = Development</li>
    <li>M = Demo</li>
    <li>R = Training</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Location</strong></p>
<p>Format: Two (2) alphabetic characters</p>
<p>Purpose: Describes the physical, logical, or geographic location in which the host resides.</p>
<p>Examples:</p>
<ul>
    <li>EP = Energy Plaza</li>
    <li>EC = Energy Control Center</li>
    <li>EX = Floats between EP and ECC</li>
    <li>AZ = Azure</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Purpose</strong></p>
<p>Format: Four (4) alphabetic characters</p>
<p>Purpose: Describes the primary purpose of the host.</p>
<p>Examples:</p>
<ul>
    <li>DOMC = Domain Controller</li>
    <li>SQLS = Microsoft SQL Server</li>
    <li>SQLC = Microsoft SQL Server Cluster</li>
    <li>GISA = GIS Application</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Identifier</strong></p>
<p>Format: Four (4) numeric characters</p>
<p>Purpose: An incremental number starting at 0001 that is used to uniquely define hosts that otherwise share the same name (i.e., share the same Platform, Form Factor, Region, Location, and Purpose).</p>
<p>Example: 0001, 0002, etc.</p>

